        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Short-form video</strong> is video content typically under 60-90 seconds, shot or cropped vertically (9:16), and distributed through algorithmic discovery feeds on platforms like TikTok, Instagram Reels, YouTube Shorts, and LinkedIn Video. Unlike broadcast video, it does not require an existing audience — the algorithm surfaces it based on watch time, completion rate, and engagement signals.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Reels, Shorts, Clips</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Short-form video is no longer a trend — it is the default content format for organic reach in 2026. Understanding how it works, which platform favours what, and how to produce it efficiently is now a core marketing competency for any brand that wants to grow without a paid media budget.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is short-form video?</h2>
        <p>Short-form video is defined less by an exact duration and more by the context in which it is consumed: a scrollable, full-screen, vertically oriented feed where the algorithm decides what comes next. The viewer is passive — they did not search for your content, they were served it. That changes everything about how you must open, structure, and close a short-form video.</p>
        <p>Platform-specific length limits in 2026:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>TikTok:</strong> up to 10 minutes, but algorithmic distribution peaks at 21-60 seconds</li>
          <li><strong>Instagram Reels:</strong> up to 90 seconds</li>
          <li><strong>YouTube Shorts:</strong> up to 60 seconds</li>
          <li><strong>LinkedIn Video:</strong> up to 10 minutes; short-form style (under 90 seconds) outperforms long-form in reach</li>
          <li><strong>Pinterest Video Pins:</strong> up to 15 minutes; sweet spot is under 30 seconds</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The practical definition that works across all platforms: if it fits in a mobile screen without letterboxing, runs under 90 seconds, and is built to be watched without sound-first, it is short-form video.</p>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How short-form video algorithms work</h2>
        <p>Every short-form video platform uses a recommendation engine that scores your video against a set of viewer behaviour signals before deciding how widely to distribute it. The core signals, in order of weight:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Video completion rate.</strong> What percentage of viewers watch to the end? A 70%+ completion rate tells the algorithm the content is holding attention and triggers wider distribution.</li>
          <li><strong>3-second view rate.</strong> How many people who saw the thumbnail or first frame watched for at least 3 seconds? This filters out misleading thumbnails and weak hooks.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-watch rate.</strong> Did people watch it more than once? Re-watches are a very strong quality signal, especially on TikTok.</li>
          <li><strong>Engagement rate.</strong> Likes, comments, shares, and saves — in that order of weight. Shares push distribution harder than any other engagement type.</li>
          <li><strong>Negative signals.</strong> "Not interested" taps, early exits, and report actions. One "not interested" from a highly relevant audience member matters more than five likes.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">How TikTok's For You Page distributes content</div>
          <p>TikTok shows every new video to a small test cohort (typically 200-500 users). If completion rate and engagement clear a threshold, it pushes the video to a larger cohort. This cascade continues until signals plateau — a video can sit for 72 hours and then spike because a large cohort responded well. You do not need followers; you need a video that holds attention.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why short-form video matters for marketing</h2>
        <p>Three platform-level shifts have made short-form video the most important organic content channel of the 2020s:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Reach without an audience.</strong> Every other content channel — blog, newsletter, podcast — requires an existing audience. Short-form video platforms will show your content to strangers based purely on quality signals. A brand new account can reach 100,000 people on its first post.</li>
          <li><strong>Sound-optional consumption.</strong> Over 70% of TikTok videos are watched without sound at some point during the session. Captions, text overlays, and visual storytelling make short-form video consumable anywhere — commute, office, waiting room.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding archive effect.</strong> A short-form video lives in the archive permanently and can be re-distributed by the algorithm weeks or months after posting. Unlike a tweet or story, it does not expire. A 6-month-old Reel can go viral today.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="structure">Anatomy of a high-performing short-form video</h2>
        <p>Every platform-tested short-form framework has four parts:</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>The Hook (0-2 seconds)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Visual pattern interrupt — something moves, cuts, or surprises</li>
              <li>Text overlay that surfaces the payoff immediately</li>
              <li>Bold claim, counterintuitive fact, or direct question</li>
              <li>Goal: earn the 3-second view and stop the scroll</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>The Body (2 seconds to end minus 3 seconds)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Deliver exactly what the hook promised — immediately</li>
              <li>Keep cuts tight — 1-3 seconds per visual beat</li>
              <li>Use captions on every video</li>
              <li>Goal: maintain watch time to 70%+ completion</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>After the body comes a brief <strong>CTA moment</strong> (1-2 seconds): "Follow for more", "Link in bio", or "Save this for later". Then, optionally, a <strong>loop trick</strong> where the last frame connects back to the first, encouraging re-watches. Re-watch loops dramatically boost TikTok distribution.</p>

        <h2 id="platforms">Platform-by-platform differences</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
