        </div>

        <h2 id="production">How to produce short-form video at scale</h2>
        <p>The biggest mistake brands make is treating each short-form video as a standalone production. Scale requires a batching system: shoot multiple videos in one session, edit in a predictable template, and schedule in advance.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Batch filming.</strong> Block 2-3 hours per week to film 8-12 raw clips. Use the same backdrop, lighting setup, and clothing. This eliminates setup overhead and lets you maintain a 5-videos-per-week publishing cadence from a single session.</li>
          <li><strong>Content series.</strong> Define 3-5 recurring formats (e.g., "Monday myth-bust", "tool tips", "before and after"). Series builds audience expectation and recycles the creative framework so you only have to write the script, not re-invent the format.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurpose from long-form.</strong> A 20-minute podcast episode contains 8-10 quotable moments. A 2,000-word blog post contains 5-6 short-form scripts. Use a content repurposing workflow to extract short-form video ideas from assets you have already created.</li>
          <li><strong>Template-first editing.</strong> Build 2-3 CapCut or Premiere templates with your brand fonts, colour accent, and caption style. Drop new footage in, replace the script text, and export. Editing time drops from 45 minutes to 8 minutes per video.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">The watermark penalty</div>
          <p>TikTok, Instagram Reels, and YouTube Shorts all algorithmically penalise videos that carry a competitor platform's watermark. A TikTok watermark on a Reels post — detectable by the in-video username overlay — gets suppressed in Instagram's distribution. Always export clean from your editing software or use a watermark-removal step before cross-posting.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for short-form video in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Open with the payoff, not the preamble.</strong> Do not introduce yourself before delivering value. Say what the video is about in the first 2 seconds. Introductions kill completion rates.</li>
          <li><strong>Add captions to every video.</strong> 70%+ of videos are watched on mute at least once. Captions are not optional — they are a reach multiplier.</li>
          <li><strong>Use trending audio strategically.</strong> Audio trends signal cultural relevance to the algorithm. Pair trending sounds with on-brand content rather than chasing trends that have no natural connection to your subject.</li>
          <li><strong>Post at audience-active times.</strong> Check platform analytics for when your existing audience is most active. If you are new, start with midday local time on Tuesday-Thursday as a baseline and iterate from there.</li>
          <li><strong>Reply with a video.</strong> TikTok's Video Reply feature — responding to a comment with a new video — is the single most underused distribution hack. The reply inherits discovery from both the original video and the comment author's audience.</li>
          <li><strong>Track completion rate, not just likes.</strong> Likes are a vanity metric for short-form video. Completion rate is the metric that predicts whether the algorithm will amplify the next video.</li>
          <li><strong>Batch and schedule.</strong> Use a social media scheduling tool to maintain publishing consistency without manual daily effort. Consistent publishing is a positive algorithmic signal on every short-form platform.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common short-form video mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Horizontal filming.</strong> Filming in landscape (16:9) and cropping to vertical (9:16) crops out the subject. Always film natively vertical or use a teleprompter rig that locks to portrait mode.</li>
          <li><strong>Slow hooks.</strong> Any intro that takes more than 2 seconds to get to the point bleeds view rate. Start mid-sentence, mid-action, or mid-result.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring comments.</strong> Comments extend the life of a video by re-triggering distribution. A video with active comments in the 48-72 hour window after posting gets a second algorithmic push.</li>
          <li><strong>Cross-posting without adapting.</strong> TikTok culture, Instagram aesthetics, and LinkedIn tone are distinct. A video that performs well on one platform often fails on another if transplanted without adjustment.</li>
          <li><strong>Deleting underperforming videos.</strong> A video that got 300 views last week may be re-served by the algorithm next month. Deleting it removes the asset permanently. Instead, let it sit — the archive has compounding value.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
